
task-1 : implement kuberneres ConfigMags and Secret
    1) modify app.py (developer)
    2) Rebuild and push docker image 
        -> docker build -t <dockehub name.app-k8s-app:v3> .
        -> docker push < dockerhub/app-k8s-app:v3>
    3) app-config and app-secret created in k8s cluster
        -> Create a ConfigMags -> store normal data
        -> Create a Secret -> store sensitive data
    4) Update Deployment to use ConfigMag and Secret
    5) apply changes to k8s cluster
        -> kubectl apply -f configmap.yaml
        -> kubectl apply -f secret.yaml
        -> kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

task-2: fix a failing jenkins pipeline caused by docker failure 
detail: your jenkins pipeline suddenly fails at the docker build stage  
    1) check requirements.txt:- update your earlier stable version or fix any version conflicts
    2) check dockerfile for any syntax errors or incorrect commands
    3) check jenkinsfile for any misconfigurations in the docker build stage
    4) check jenkins agent/node has docker installed and running
    5) check disk space on jenkins agent/node
    6) check network connectivity from jenkins agent/node to docker registry
    7) check docker daemon logs for any specific error messages

Task-3: add resource request and limit in k8 deployment
    -> current deployemt.yaml is weak no production-ready app should run without resource policies
        today we fix this 
    1) analyze app resource usage using kubectl top pod <pod-name>
    2) update deployment.yaml to add resource requests and limits

Task-4: Update deployemt to use ConfigMap and Secret
    1) create configmap.yaml to store non-sensitive data
    2) create secret.yaml to store sensitive data
    3) update deployment.yaml to mount configmap and secret as env variables or volume mounts
    4) apply changes to k8s cluster
        -> kubectl apply -f configmap.yaml
        -> kubectl apply -f secret.yaml
        -> kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

Task-5: Add liveness and readiness probes to k8s deployment
        ->liveness:- if your app is hanga, stuck or dead, restart it.
        ->readiness:- if your app is not ready to serve traffic, stop sending traffic to it.no customer-facing downtime
    1) analyze app health check endpoints
    2) update deployment.yaml to add liveness and readiness probes
    3) apply changes to k8s cluster
        -> kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
        kubectl describe deployment <deployment-name> to verify probes are configured
        you must see liveness succeded and readiness succeded
        
task-6: Create Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) for k8s deployment
    1) analyze app resource usage using kubectl top pod <pod-name>
    2) create hpa.yaml to define HPA configuration based on cpu/memory usage
    3) apply hpa to k8s cluster
        -> kubectl apply -f hpa.yaml
    4) verify HPA is working
        -> kubectl get hpa <hpa-name>
        -> generate load on app to trigger scaling 
        -> kubectl get pods to see new pods being created